{
  "texts": [
    "u 1 ≤ u 2 ≤... ≤ u n, the probability to select a product i from the offer set S is given by These probabilities can be obtained in closed form as the loglikelihood function is concave, and thus, maximum likelihood estimation can be used to determine the model parameters defining the deterministic component of the utility.",
    "Note that without loss of generality, one typically takes = 1 and rescales the u's accordingly.",
    "Under the Markov chain choice model (MCC) proposed by Blanchet et al. (2016), the consumer choice process is represented by a Markov chain with N + 1 states.",
    "Each state i corresponds to a product or the no-purchase option.",
    "If product i is offered, a customer that arrives at state i purchases this product; otherwise the customer proceeds to another state j."
  ]
}